---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="FAQ | Grithos"
  description="Common questions about Grithos — is it a religion, a cult, or just Stoicism? Straight answers about a philosophy of life built on grit and ethos."
  ogTitle="FAQ — Grithos"
  ogDescription="Common questions about Grithos. Straight answers. No fluff. Is it a religion? Is it a cult? Is it just Stoicism? Find out."
  ogUrl="https://grithos.com/faq"
  canonical="https://grithos.com/faq"
  activePage="faq"
>

<Fragment slot="head">
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does Grithos conflict with faith or religious belief?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Grithos was born from faith, not in spite of it. The core of Grithos — showing up, loving without flinching, moving forward with purpose even when it's hard — is entirely consistent with a life of genuine faith. Grit and grace are not opposites. Some people will disagree. Some have said so directly. That's okay. Grithos doesn't ask you to abandon your beliefs — it asks you to live them with confidence and conviction, even when circumstances are hard, even when people judge your path, even when the road looks nothing like you planned. Faith without action is just wishful thinking. Grithos is the action."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is Grithos a religion?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Grithos is a philosophy of life — a framework for how to think, act, and live. It acknowledges God as the architect of the bounds but does not prescribe how to worship, what to believe about the afterlife, or which faith to follow. Your relationship with God is yours. Grithos asks only that you also align with virtue, effort, and the life you were given."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is this a cult?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. There is no membership, no dues, no leader to obey, no group identity to adopt. Grithos is a set of ideas. You take what serves you. You leave what doesn't. Nobody tracks you, pressures you, or asks you to recruit anyone. If it helps you live better, use it. If it doesn't, move on."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is this just Stoicism?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Grithos draws heavily from Stoic philosophy — especially Marcus Aurelius' Meditations. But it is not a copy. Stoicism counsels emotional detachment; Grithos says feel everything, then move. Stoicism is indifferent to outcomes; Grithos says fight for the outcome, but redirect when the bounds decide otherwise. Stoicism is ancient theory. Grithos is modern practice."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do I have to believe in God to follow Grithos?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Grithos acknowledges a rational God who authored the bounds — the consistent, trustworthy laws that govern reality. If you believe in God, Grithos does not conflict with that. If you see 'the bounds' as natural law or physics, the philosophy still works. Grithos does not require a specific belief — it requires alignment with reality."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I be Christian and follow Grithos?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. Grithos was specifically written to avoid conflicting with Christian beliefs. It does not deny God, dismiss worship, or reject the afterlife. It says: however you choose to honor God is yours. The tenets — honesty, keeping your word, protecting others, building legacy — align with Christian values."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is a Grithosian?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A Grithosian (grith-OH-see-an) is someone who practices the Grithos philosophy. There is no initiation, no card, no ceremony. If you live by the tenets, you are a Grithosian. If you stop, you are not. It is defined entirely by action."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does 'the bounds' mean?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The bounds are the rules of reality — gravity, time, cause and effect, biology, physics. They are consistent, rational, and trustworthy. God authored them. A Grithosian does not fight the bounds or wish for different ones. You learn them, respect them, and build within them."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why was Grithos founded on Friday the 13th?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Because superstition fears that date. Grithos was forged in it. A Grithosian does not avoid things because of irrational fear. Friday the 13th is just a day — and now it is Forge Day, the founding day of Grithos. Every Friday the 13th, you do one hard thing on purpose. Something you've been avoiding. Something that tests you. No ceremony required. Just action."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do I have to follow all 15 tenets?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The tenets are a complete system — each one reinforces the others. Start with the one that challenges you most. Practice it until it becomes natural. Then add another. The goal is not perfection. The goal is daily, deliberate effort. Show up. Do the work."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Who is Marcus Aurelius and why does he matter?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Marcus Aurelius was the Emperor of Rome from 161 to 180 AD and one of history's greatest Stoic philosophers. He wrote Meditations — a private journal of self-discipline and moral reflection. Grithos did not invent its principles. It inherited them. The ideas behind the Five Pillars have been tested for nearly two thousand years."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is Verity?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Verity is the fifth pillar of Grithos. It means truth in the age of engineered information. A Grithosian does not consume passively — they verify, question, and think before they accept. Verity is the discipline of knowing what is real."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why did Grithos add a fifth pillar?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Because the world changed. AI, algorithmic feeds, and synthetic content created threats to truth that didn't exist before. The original four pillars assumed you could trust what you saw. Verity exists because that assumption is no longer safe."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does 'Build With, Never Build Under' mean?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "It means use tools — including AI — to amplify what you build. But never let a tool become your master. You direct. You decide. You own the outcome. The moment you defer your judgment to a machine, you've built under it."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does Grithos hate technology?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Grithos embraces tools that serve human agency. A hammer doesn't think for you. AI shouldn't either. The issue is never the technology — it's whether you control it or it controls you."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I use AI and still be a Grithosian?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Absolutely. Grithos was partly built with AI tools. The question is not whether you use AI — it's whether you remain the one thinking, deciding, and owning the result. Use it. Don't serve it."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does 'The Engineered Age' mean?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The Engineered Age is the era we live in now — where information, attention, and even emotion are manufactured at scale. Algorithms decide what you see. AI generates what you read. A Grithosian recognizes this and guards their mind accordingly."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does 'A Grithosian does not sleep' mean?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "It does not mean deprive yourself of rest. It means a Grithosian does not sleepwalk through life. No autopilot. No drifting. Every day has purpose and direction. You are awake to your choices, your time, and your responsibilities."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How does Grithos view social media?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Social media is a tool. Like any tool, it can build or it can destroy. Grithos says: use it with intention. Post with purpose. Consume with discipline. If scrolling is your default state, you've surrendered your attention to someone else's agenda."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is Grithos anti-AI?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Grithos is anti-surrender. AI is one of the most powerful tools ever created. The danger is not the tool — it's humans who stop thinking because the tool thinks for them. Stay sovereign over your own mind."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What's the difference between using AI and serving AI?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Using AI means you set the goal, direct the work, and verify the output. Serving AI means you accept whatever it gives you without question, let it shape your opinions, or can't function without it. One is mastery. The other is dependency."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How is Grithos different from self-help?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Self-help tells you to feel better. Grithos tells you to be better — and gives you the structure to do it. No affirmations. No vision boards. Fifteen tenets, five pillars, daily practice. It's a framework, not a feeling."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the Five Pillars?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The Five Pillars are Virtue, Apex, Control, Death, and Verity. They are the structural foundation of Grithos — everything else hangs from them. Each pillar contains three tenets that define how a Grithosian lives."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the Daily Practice?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The Daily Practice is a short morning reflection delivered at 5:55 AM. One tenet. One thought. One actionable challenge for the day. It's how Grithos stays alive in your life — not as a book on a shelf, but as a daily discipline."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I start?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Read the tenets. Pick the one that hits hardest. Practice it today. That's it. There's no onboarding, no course to buy, no level to unlock. Grithos starts when you decide to show up."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I practice Grithos alone or do I need a community?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Grithos is a solo practice first. You against your own excuses, every day. Community helps — iron sharpens iron — but it is not required. A Grithosian who practices alone is still a Grithosian."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does 'Redirect Immediately' mean?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "When something breaks — a plan fails, a door closes, life hits — you don't sit in the wreckage. You redirect. Immediately. Not after grieving for a week. Not after blaming someone. You assess what's real, pick a new heading, and move."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does 'Own Your Nature' mean?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "It means stop pretending to be something you're not. Know your strengths. Know your flaws. Work with both. A Grithosian doesn't perform a personality — they own who they actually are and build from that truth."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is Grithos only for men?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Grithos is for anyone willing to do the work. The tenets don't have a gender requirement. Honesty, discipline, protecting what matters, building legacy — these are human virtues, not male ones."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does Grithos promote toxic masculinity?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Grithos promotes accountability, emotional honesty, and showing up for the people who depend on you. That's not toxic — that's what masculinity was supposed to be before the term got weaponized. Strength without virtue is just violence. Grithos demands both."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does 'Return to the Whole' mean?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "It means death is not a tragedy — it's a transition. You came from the whole, you return to the whole. A Grithosian does not fear death. They use its certainty to fuel urgency in life. Every day matters because your days are numbered."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is there a Grithos app?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Not yet. The Daily Practice is currently delivered by email. An app may come, but only when it genuinely serves the mission — not as a vanity project. Grithos doesn't need an app. It needs practitioners."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much does Grithos cost?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Nothing. The philosophy, the tenets, the Daily Practice — all free. Grithos exists to help people live better, not to extract money. Future offerings like merch or courses may come, but the core will always be free."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Who created Grithos?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Richard Johnson. A cybersecurity professional, Airstream dweller, and lifelong practitioner of Stoic philosophy who decided the world needed something sharper than self-help and more practical than ancient texts. Grithos is what he built."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I teach Grithos to my kids?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. In fact, the tenets were written to be teachable. Honesty, keeping your word, owning your mistakes, protecting others — these are lessons every kid needs. Start with one tenet. Live it in front of them. Kids learn what they see."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is there a Grithos book?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Not yet. The philosophy is documented on grithos.com and in the Daily Practice. A book is planned but not rushed. When it comes, it will be the definitive text — not a quick cash grab."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is The Footing?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The Footing is the foundational document of Grithos — its declaration of purpose and principles. Think of it as the constitution. Everything else — the pillars, the tenets, the practice — flows from The Footing."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are The Architects?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The Architects are the thinkers whose ideas shaped Grithos — Marcus Aurelius, Seneca, Epictetus, and others. Grithos did not emerge from nothing. It stands on the shoulders of people who spent their lives testing these principles."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I become a Grithosian?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Live the tenets. That's it. There's no application, no initiation, no approval process. You become a Grithosian by practicing Grithos. You stop being one when you stop. It's defined by what you do, not what you claim."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is Forge Day and how do I observe it?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Forge Day is the founding day of Grithos — every Friday the 13th. You observe it by doing one hard thing on purpose. Something you've been avoiding. Something that tests you. No ceremony required. Just action."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can businesses adopt Grithos principles?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. Honesty, accountability, keeping your word, protecting your people, building something that outlasts you — these aren't just personal virtues. They're the foundation of any business worth building. The tenets scale from one person to an organization."
        }
      }
    ]
  })} />
</Fragment>

<style is:inline>
  .page-hero {
    padding: 80px 0 40px;
    text-align: center;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .page-hero::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    top: 40%; left: 50%; transform: translateX(-50%);
    width: 800px; height: 800px;
    background: radial-gradient(circle, rgba(196,168,130,.05) 0%, transparent 70%);
    pointer-events: none;
    z-index: 0;
  }
  .page-hero-overline {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: clamp(14px, 2vw, 18px);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: .3em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--gold);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
  }
  .page-hero-title {
    font-family: var(--heading);
    font-size: clamp(32px, 4.5vw, 52px);
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 1.1;
    letter-spacing: -.02em;
    color: var(--white);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
  }
  .page-hero-sub {
    font-family: var(--serif);
    font-size: clamp(15px, 2vw, 18px);
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    max-width: 560px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    line-height: 1.7;
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
  }

  .faq-section {
    padding: 0 0 100px;
  }
  .faq-list {
    max-width: 760px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .faq-item {
    background: var(--card);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 10px;
    padding: 24px 28px;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
    cursor: pointer;
    transition: all .3s;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .faq-item:hover {
    border-color: var(--gold-border);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }
  .faq-item.open {
    border-color: var(--gold-border);
  }
  .faq-question {
    width: 100%;
    background: none;
    border: none;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 16px;
    cursor: pointer;
    text-align: left;
  }
  .faq-question-text {
    font-family: var(--heading);
    font-size: 17px;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--white);
    line-height: 1.4;
    transition: color .2s;
  }
  .faq-item:hover .faq-question-text {
    color: var(--gold);
  }
  .faq-icon {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 28px;
    height: 28px;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 50%;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    transition: all .3s;
  }
  .faq-icon svg {
    width: 14px;
    height: 14px;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    transition: all .3s;
  }
  .faq-item.open .faq-icon {
    border-color: var(--gold);
    background: var(--gold-soft);
  }
  .faq-item.open .faq-icon svg {
    color: var(--gold);
    transform: rotate(45deg);
  }
  .faq-answer {
    max-height: 0;
    overflow: hidden;
    transition: max-height .4s cubic-bezier(.16,1,.3,1), opacity .3s;
    opacity: 0;
  }
  .faq-item.open .faq-answer {
    opacity: 1;
  }
  .faq-answer-inner {
    padding: 16px 0 4px;
    font-family: var(--serif);
    font-size: 16px;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.8;
    max-width: 640px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    margin-top: 16px;
  }
  .faq-answer-inner a {
    color: var(--gold);
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: color .2s;
  }
  .faq-answer-inner a:hover {
    color: var(--gold-light);
  }

  @media(max-width:768px) {
    .faq-question-text {
      font-size: 16px;
    }
  }
</style>

<section class="page-hero">
  <div class="wrap">
    <img src="/assets/images/grithos-logo.png" alt="Grithos" style="width: 120px; height: auto; margin-bottom: 16px; opacity: 0.85;">
    <p class="page-hero-overline reveal">FAQ</p>
    <h1 class="page-hero-title reveal d1">Straight Answers</h1>
    <p class="page-hero-sub reveal d2">No fluff. No spin. Just the questions people ask and the honest answers.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="faq-section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="faq-list">

      <div class="faq-item reveal d1">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Does Grithos conflict with faith or religious belief?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">No. Grithos was born from faith, not in spite of it. The core of Grithos — showing up, loving without flinching, moving forward with purpose even when it's hard — is entirely consistent with a life of genuine faith. Grit and grace are not opposites. Some people will disagree. Some have said so directly. That's okay. Grithos doesn't ask you to abandon your beliefs — it asks you to live them with confidence and conviction, even when circumstances are hard, even when people judge your path, even when the road looks nothing like you planned. Faith without action is just wishful thinking. Grithos is the action.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d2">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Is Grithos a religion?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">No. Grithos is a philosophy of life — a framework for how to think, act, and live. It acknowledges God as the architect of the bounds but does not prescribe how to worship, what to believe about the afterlife, or which faith to follow. Your relationship with God is yours. Grithos asks only that you also align with virtue, effort, and the life you were given.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d3">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Is this a cult?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">No. There is no membership, no dues, no leader to obey, no group identity to adopt. Grithos is a set of ideas. You take what serves you. You leave what doesn't. Nobody tracks you, pressures you, or asks you to recruit anyone. If it helps you live better, use it. If it doesn't, move on.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d4">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Is this just Stoicism?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Grithos draws heavily from Stoic philosophy — especially Marcus Aurelius' <a href="/architects">Meditations</a>. But it is not a copy. Stoicism counsels emotional detachment; Grithos says feel everything, then move. Stoicism is indifferent to outcomes; Grithos says fight for the outcome, but redirect when the bounds decide otherwise. Stoicism is ancient theory. Grithos is modern practice.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d5">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Do I have to believe in God to follow Grithos?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Grithos acknowledges a rational God who authored the bounds — the consistent, trustworthy laws that govern reality. If you believe in God, Grithos does not conflict with that. If you see "the bounds" as natural law or physics, the philosophy still works. Grithos does not require a specific belief — it requires alignment with reality.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d6">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Can I be Christian and follow Grithos?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes. Grithos was specifically written to avoid conflicting with Christian beliefs. It does not deny God, dismiss worship, or reject the afterlife. It says: however you choose to honor God is yours. The <a href="/tenets">tenets</a> — honesty, keeping your word, protecting others, building legacy — align with Christian values.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d7">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What is a Grithosian?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">A Grithosian (grith-OH-see-an) is someone who practices the Grithos philosophy. There is no initiation, no card, no ceremony. If you live by the tenets, you are a Grithosian. If you stop, you are not. It is defined entirely by action.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What does "the bounds" mean?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">The bounds are the rules of reality — gravity, time, cause and effect, biology, physics. They are consistent, rational, and trustworthy. God authored them. A Grithosian does not fight the bounds or wish for different ones. You learn them, respect them, and build within them.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Why was Grithos founded on Friday the 13th?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Because superstition fears that date. Grithos was forged in it. A Grithosian does not avoid things because of irrational fear. Friday the 13th is just a day — and now it is <a href="/practice">Forge Day</a>, the founding day of Grithos. Every Friday the 13th, you do one hard thing on purpose. Something you've been avoiding. Something that tests you. No ceremony required. Just action.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Do I have to follow all 15 tenets?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">The <a href="/tenets">tenets</a> are a complete system — each one reinforces the others. But nobody is grading you. Start with the one that challenges you most. Practice it until it becomes natural. Then add another. The goal is not perfection. The goal is daily effort toward a better version of yourself.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Who is Marcus Aurelius and why does he matter?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Marcus Aurelius was the Emperor of Rome from 161 to 180 AD and one of history's greatest Stoic philosophers. He wrote <em>Meditations</em> — a private journal of self-discipline and moral reflection. Grithos did not invent its principles. It inherited them. The ideas behind the <a href="/architects">Five Pillars</a> have been tested for nearly two thousand years.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Verity / AI Age -->

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What is Verity?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Verity is the fifth pillar of Grithos. It means truth in the age of engineered information. A Grithosian does not consume passively — they verify, question, and think before they accept. Verity is the discipline of knowing what is real.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Why did Grithos add a fifth pillar?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Because the world changed. AI, algorithmic feeds, and synthetic content created threats to truth that didn't exist before. The original four pillars assumed you could trust what you saw. Verity exists because that assumption is no longer safe.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What does &ldquo;Build With, Never Build Under&rdquo; mean?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">It means use tools — including AI — to amplify what you build. But never let a tool become your master. You direct. You decide. You own the outcome. The moment you defer your judgment to a machine, you've built under it.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Does Grithos hate technology?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">No. Grithos embraces tools that serve human agency. A hammer doesn't think for you. AI shouldn't either. The issue is never the technology — it's whether you control it or it controls you.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Can I use AI and still be a Grithosian?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Absolutely. Grithos was partly built with AI tools. The question is not whether you use AI — it's whether you remain the one thinking, deciding, and owning the result. Use it. Don't serve it.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What does &ldquo;The Engineered Age&rdquo; mean?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">The Engineered Age is the era we live in now — where information, attention, and even emotion are manufactured at scale. Algorithms decide what you see. AI generates what you read. A Grithosian recognizes this and guards their mind accordingly.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What does &ldquo;A Grithosian does not sleep&rdquo; mean?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">It does not mean deprive yourself of rest. It means a Grithosian does not sleepwalk through life. No autopilot. No drifting. Every day has purpose and direction. You are awake to your choices, your time, and your responsibilities.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">How does Grithos view social media?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Social media is a tool. Like any tool, it can build or it can destroy. Grithos says: use it with intention. Post with purpose. Consume with discipline. If scrolling is your default state, you've surrendered your attention to someone else's agenda.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Is Grithos anti-AI?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">No. Grithos is anti-surrender. AI is one of the most powerful tools ever created. The danger is not the tool — it's humans who stop thinking because the tool thinks for them. Stay sovereign over your own mind.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What&rsquo;s the difference between using AI and serving AI?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Using AI means you set the goal, direct the work, and verify the output. Serving AI means you accept whatever it gives you without question, let it shape your opinions, or can't function without it. One is mastery. The other is dependency.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Philosophy & Practice -->

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">How is Grithos different from self-help?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Self-help tells you to feel better. Grithos tells you to <em>be</em> better — and gives you the structure to do it. No affirmations. No vision boards. Fifteen <a href="/tenets">tenets</a>, five pillars, daily practice. It's a framework, not a feeling.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What are the Five Pillars?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">The Five Pillars are Virtue, Apex, Control, Death, and Verity. They are the structural foundation of Grithos — everything else hangs from them. Each pillar contains three <a href="/tenets">tenets</a> that define how a Grithosian lives.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What is the Daily Practice?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">The <a href="/practice">Daily Practice</a> is a short morning reflection delivered at 5:55 AM. One tenet. One thought. One actionable challenge for the day. It's how Grithos stays alive in your life — not as a book on a shelf, but as a daily discipline.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">How do I start?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Read the <a href="/tenets">tenets</a>. Pick the one that hits hardest. Practice it today. That's it. There's no onboarding, no course to buy, no level to unlock. Grithos starts when you decide to show up.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Can I practice Grithos alone or do I need a community?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Grithos is a solo practice first. You against your own excuses, every day. Community helps — iron sharpens iron — but it is not required. A Grithosian who practices alone is still a Grithosian.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What does &ldquo;Redirect Immediately&rdquo; mean?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">When something breaks — a plan fails, a door closes, life hits — you don't sit in the wreckage. You redirect. Immediately. Not after grieving for a week. Not after blaming someone. You assess what's real, pick a new heading, and move.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What does &ldquo;Own Your Nature&rdquo; mean?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">It means stop pretending to be something you're not. Know your strengths. Know your flaws. Work with both. A Grithosian doesn't perform a personality — they own who they actually are and build from that truth.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Is Grithos only for men?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">No. Grithos is for anyone willing to do the work. The <a href="/tenets">tenets</a> don't have a gender requirement. Honesty, discipline, protecting what matters, building legacy — these are human virtues, not male ones.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Does Grithos promote toxic masculinity?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">No. Grithos promotes accountability, emotional honesty, and showing up for the people who depend on you. That's not toxic — that's what masculinity was supposed to be before the term got weaponized. Strength without virtue is just violence. Grithos demands both.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What does &ldquo;Return to the Whole&rdquo; mean?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">It means death is not a tragedy — it's a transition. You came from the whole, you return to the whole. A Grithosian does not fear death. They use its certainty to fuel urgency in life. Every day matters because your days are numbered.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Practical / Personal -->

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Is there a Grithos app?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Not yet. The <a href="/practice">Daily Practice</a> is currently delivered by email. An app may come, but only when it genuinely serves the mission — not as a vanity project. Grithos doesn't need an app. It needs practitioners.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">How much does Grithos cost?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Nothing. The philosophy, the tenets, the Daily Practice — all free. Grithos exists to help people live better, not to extract money. Future offerings like merch or courses may come, but the core will always be free.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Who created Grithos?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Richard Johnson. A cybersecurity professional, Airstream dweller, and lifelong practitioner of Stoic philosophy who decided the world needed something sharper than self-help and more practical than ancient texts. Grithos is what he built.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Can I teach Grithos to my kids?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes. In fact, the <a href="/tenets">tenets</a> were written to be teachable. Honesty, keeping your word, owning your mistakes, protecting others — these are lessons every kid needs. Start with one tenet. Live it in front of them. Kids learn what they see.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Is there a Grithos book?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Not yet. The philosophy is documented on grithos.com and in the <a href="/practice">Daily Practice</a>. A book is planned but not rushed. When it comes, it will be the definitive text — not a quick cash grab.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What is The Footing?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner"><a href="/footing">The Footing</a> is the foundational document of Grithos — its declaration of purpose and principles. Think of it as the constitution. Everything else — the pillars, the tenets, the practice — flows from The Footing.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What are The Architects?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner"><a href="/architects">The Architects</a> are the thinkers whose ideas shaped Grithos — Marcus Aurelius, Seneca, Epictetus, and others. Grithos did not emerge from nothing. It stands on the shoulders of people who spent their lives testing these principles.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">How do I become a Grithosian?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Live the <a href="/tenets">tenets</a>. That's it. There's no application, no initiation, no approval process. You become a Grithosian by practicing Grithos. You stop being one when you stop. It's defined by what you do, not what you claim.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">What is Forge Day and how do I observe it?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Forge Day is the founding day of Grithos — every Friday the 13th. You observe it by doing one hard thing on purpose. Something you've been avoiding. Something that tests you. No ceremony required. Just action.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item reveal d8">
        <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="faq-question-text">Can businesses adopt Grithos principles?</span>
          <span class="faq-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="2.5" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4.5v15m7.5-7.5h-15" /></svg></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes. Honesty, accountability, keeping your word, protecting your people, building something that outlasts you — these aren't just personal virtues. They're the foundation of any business worth building. The <a href="/tenets">tenets</a> scale from one person to an organization.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<script is:inline>
(function() {
  document.querySelectorAll('.faq-question').forEach(function(btn) {
    btn.addEventListener('click', function() {
      var item = btn.closest('.faq-item');
      var answer = item.querySelector('.faq-answer');
      var isOpen = item.classList.contains('open');

      // Close all others
      document.querySelectorAll('.faq-item.open').forEach(function(openItem) {
        if (openItem !== item) {
          openItem.classList.remove('open');
          openItem.querySelector('.faq-question').setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');
          openItem.querySelector('.faq-answer').style.maxHeight = '0';
        }
      });

      if (isOpen) {
        item.classList.remove('open');
        btn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');
        answer.style.maxHeight = '0';
      } else {
        item.classList.add('open');
        btn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'true');
        answer.style.maxHeight = answer.scrollHeight + 'px';
      }
    });
  });
})();
</script>

</BaseLayout>
